hook.real_world_problem:
You're testing a discount calculator:

```java
double getDiscount(int qty) {
    if (qty >= 50) return 0.20;
    if (qty >= 10) return 0.10;
    return 0.0;
}
```

Naive approach — four separate tests, almost identical:
```java
@Test void qty1_noDiscount()  { assertEquals(0.0,  calc.getDiscount(1));  }
@Test void qty9_noDiscount()  { assertEquals(0.0,  calc.getDiscount(9));  }
@Test void qty10_10percent()  { assertEquals(0.10, calc.getDiscount(10)); }
@Test void qty50_20percent()  { assertEquals(0.20, calc.getDiscount(50)); }
```

But wait — what about qty=0? qty=-1? qty=49? qty=51? qty=Integer.MAX_VALUE?

**The professional approach — one parameterized test:**
```java
@ParameterizedTest
@CsvSource({
    "1,  0.00",  // below threshold
    "9,  0.00",  // boundary - 1
    "10, 0.10",  // boundary exactly
    "11, 0.10",  // boundary + 1
    "49, 0.10",  // second boundary - 1
    "50, 0.20",  // second boundary exactly
    "51, 0.20",  // second boundary + 1
    "100,0.20"   // well above
})
void getDiscount_variousQuantities_returnsCorrectDiscount(int qty, double expected) {
    assertEquals(expected, calc.getDiscount(qty), 0.001);
}
```

Eight test cases. One test method. Every boundary covered. Every off-by-one would be caught. This is parameterized testing.

concept_explanation.value_source:
**`@ValueSource` — single values of one type:**

```java
import org.junit.jupiter.params.*;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.provider.*;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

// Test a single int parameter:
@ParameterizedTest
@ValueSource(ints = {1, 9, 10, 49, 50, 100})
void getDiscount_variousQtys_returnExpected(int qty) {
    // One test method, 6 executions
    double result = calc.getDiscount(qty);
    assertTrue(result >= 0 && result <= 1.0, "Discount must be between 0 and 1");
}

// String inputs:
@ParameterizedTest
@ValueSource(strings = {"Aisha", "Raj", "Priya", "Vikram"})
void greet_anyName_returnsHello(String name) {
    assertTrue(greeter.greet(name).startsWith("Hello, "));
}

// Other supported types:
@ValueSource(longs  = {1L, 100L, Long.MAX_VALUE})
@ValueSource(doubles = {0.1, 1.0, 99.9})
@ValueSource(booleans = {true, false})
@ValueSource(chars  = {'a', 'z', '0', ' '})
@ValueSource(classes = {String.class, Integer.class})
```

concept_explanation.csv_source:
**`@CsvSource` — multiple parameters per test:**

```java
// Multiple columns: 'input, expected'
@ParameterizedTest
@CsvSource({
    "Mouse,       799, true",
    "Keyboard,   1999, true",
    "'',          799, false",   // empty string — use single quotes in CSV
    "Monitor,       0, false",   // zero price
    "Headphones, -100, false"    // negative price
})
void isValidProduct_variousInputs(String name, int price, boolean expected) {
    assertEquals(expected, validator.isValid(new Product(name, price)));
}

// Null values in CsvSource:
@ParameterizedTest
@CsvSource(value = {
    "Aisha, 28",
    "Raj,   25",
    ", 28"    // first param will be null
})
void processUser_variousInputs(String name, int age) {
    // name is null in the third case
    assertDoesNotThrow(() -> userService.process(name, age));
}

// @CsvFileSource for reading from a file:
@ParameterizedTest
@CsvFileSource(resources = "/test-data.csv", numLinesToSkip = 1)
void loadFromFile(String input, String expected) { ... }
```

concept_explanation.method_source:
**`@MethodSource` — complex objects and streams:**

```java
import java.util.stream.Stream;
import org.junit.jupiter.params.provider.Arguments;

@ParameterizedTest
@MethodSource("validProducts")  // method name in same class
void processProduct_validInputs_succeeds(Product product) {
    assertDoesNotThrow(() -> service.process(product));
}

// Supplier method — must be static, returns Stream:
static Stream<Product> validProducts() {
    return Stream.of(
        new Product("Mouse",     799),
        new Product("Keyboard", 1999),
        new Product("Monitor", 18999)
    );
}

// Multiple arguments — use Arguments.of():
@ParameterizedTest
@MethodSource("discountScenarios")
void getDiscount_scenarios(int qty, double expected, String description) {
    assertEquals(expected, calc.getDiscount(qty), 0.001, description);
}

static Stream<Arguments> discountScenarios() {
    return Stream.of(
        Arguments.of(1,  0.00, "no discount below 10"),
        Arguments.of(10, 0.10, "10% at boundary"),
        Arguments.of(50, 0.20, "20% at boundary")
    );
}
```

concept_explanation.null_empty_source:
**`@NullAndEmptySource` — null and empty inputs:**

```java
// Most methods should handle null/empty gracefully:
@ParameterizedTest
@NullAndEmptySource  // runs twice: once with null, once with empty string
void search_nullOrEmpty_returnsEmptyList(String query) {
    List<Product> result = search.find(query);
    assertNotNull(result);
    assertTrue(result.isEmpty());
}

// Combine with @ValueSource:
@ParameterizedTest
@NullAndEmptySource
@ValueSource(strings = {" ", "  ", "\t"})  // blank strings too
void search_blankInput_returnsEmptyList(String query) {
    assertTrue(search.find(query).isEmpty());
}
```

concept_explanation.enum_source:
**`@EnumSource` — test against enum values:**

```java
enum PaymentMethod { CARD, UPI, NET_BANKING, WALLET }

// Test all enum values:
@ParameterizedTest
@EnumSource(PaymentMethod.class)
void processPayment_allMethods_returnsSuccess(PaymentMethod method) {
    PaymentResult result = processor.process(100.0, method);
    assertEquals("SUCCESS", result.status());
}

// Test specific values only:
@ParameterizedTest
@EnumSource(value = PaymentMethod.class, names = {"CARD", "UPI"})
void processPayment_onlineMethod_chargesFee(PaymentMethod method) {
    assertTrue(processor.getFee(method) > 0);
}

// Exclude specific values:
@ParameterizedTest
@EnumSource(value = PaymentMethod.class, names = {"WALLET"}, mode = EnumSource.Mode.EXCLUDE)
void processPayment_nonWallet_requiresAuth(PaymentMethod method) {
    assertTrue(processor.requiresAuthentication(method));
}
```

concept_explanation.boundary_value_testing:
**Boundary value analysis — the systematic approach:**

For any range `[min, max]`, test: below min, at min, just above min, middle, just below max, at max, above max.

```java
// Discount rule: qty < 10 → 0%, qty >= 10 → 10%, qty >= 50 → 20%
// Boundaries: 10 and 50
// Test: 9 (below), 10 (at), 11 (above), 49 (below), 50 (at), 51 (above)

@ParameterizedTest
@CsvSource({
    "0,  0.00",   // zero
    "1,  0.00",   // just above zero
    "9,  0.00",   // boundary 1 - 1
    "10, 0.10",   // boundary 1 exactly
    "11, 0.10",   // boundary 1 + 1
    "49, 0.10",   // boundary 2 - 1
    "50, 0.20",   // boundary 2 exactly
    "51, 0.20",   // boundary 2 + 1
    "-1, 0.00"    // below zero (or should throw)
})
void discount_boundaryValues(int qty, double expected) {
    assertEquals(expected, calc.getDiscount(qty), 0.001);
}

// Equivalence partitioning: group inputs with the same expected behaviour:
// Partition 1: qty < 10 → 0% (test any value: 1, 5, 9)
// Partition 2: 10 <= qty < 50 → 10% (test: 10, 25, 49)
// Partition 3: qty >= 50 → 20% (test: 50, 75, 100)
```

